---
date: 2025-11-21
title: Teaching Break (Release Cue) - Training Protocol
layout: post
---

## **THE PROBLEM**

**What's Happening:**

- Sometimes Melon breaks when you say "break"
- Sometimes she just sits there staring at you
- She hasn't connected "break" = "you're done, you can move now"
- You're not always sure if she's "in position" to release from

**Why This Happens:** "Break" hasn't been taught systematically as a distinct behavior. It's just a word you sometimes say, without clear meaning or consistent pattern.

---

## **THE TWO-PART ISSUE**

### **Problem 1: "Break" Isn't Clear to Her Yet**

She doesn't understand that "break" means "you're released from that behavior, you can move now."

### **Problem 2: You Can't Always Tell If She's "In Position"**

Without clear visibility (mesh crate) or clear criteria (what counts as "on place"?), you can't confidently release her FROM a behavior.

**Solution:** Define clear criteria + teach "break" systematically.

---

## **STEP 1: DEFINE YOUR POSITIONS CLEARLY**

Before you can release her, you need to know EXACTLY what you're releasing her from.

### **Clear Criteria for Each Behavior:**

|**Behavior**|**Clear Criteria**|**How You Know She's "In It"**|
|---|---|---|
|**Place**|All 4 paws on the bed|You can see all 4 paws touching the bed|
|**Sit**|Butt on ground, front paws on ground|You can see her butt down, not shifting weight|
|**Down**|Belly on ground, elbows down|You can see her elbows touching ground|
|**Wait (meals)**|Not moving toward bowl|She's stationary (sit/stand/down - doesn't matter)|

**Write these down.** Your criteria need to be binary: "Is she in position? Yes or no?"

---

## **STEP 2: TEACH "BREAK" AS A STANDALONE BEHAVIOR**

### **Phase 1: Place Bed + Toss (Building the Association)**

**Goal:** She learns "break" = permission to leave the bed.

**Training Protocol:**

|**Step**|**You Do**|**She Does**|**Result**|
|---|---|---|---|
|1|Cue "place"|Gets on bed (all 4 paws)|-|
|2|Wait 2 seconds|Stays on bed|-|
|3|Say "BREAK" + toss treat off bed|Jumps off to get treat|Learns "break" = leave the bed|

**Frequency:** 20 reps per session, 2-3 sessions per day for 3 days.

**Success Metric:** She consistently leaves the bed when she hears "break."

---

### **Phase 2: Place Bed + Delay the Toss (Building the Cue)**

**Goal:** She starts moving when she hears "break," BEFORE you toss the treat.

**Training Protocol:**

|**Step**|**You Do**|**She Does**|**Result**|
|---|---|---|---|
|1|Cue "place"|Gets on bed|-|
|2|Wait 3-5 seconds|Stays on bed|-|
|3|Say "BREAK"|**WAIT 1 SECOND**|She should start to move|
|4|Toss treat as she's moving off|Gets treat|"Break" = the CUE, not just a word with the toss|

**Frequency:** 15-20 reps per session, 2-3 sessions per day for 3-5 days.

**Success Metric:** She begins moving off the bed when she hears "break," before the treat is tossed.

---

### **Phase 3: Place Bed + No Toss Needed (Cue is Established)**

**Goal:** "Break" is a real release cue that works without luring.

**Training Protocol:**

|**Step**|**You Do**|**She Does**|**Result**|
|---|---|---|---|
|1|Cue "place"|Gets on bed|-|
|2|Wait 5 seconds|Stays on bed|-|
|3|Say "BREAK"|Gets off bed on her own|Jackpot reward AFTER she's off|

**Frequency:** 10-15 reps per session, 2-3 sessions per day for 3-5 days.

**Success Metric:** She reliably leaves the bed when she hears "break," no toss needed.

---

## **STEP 3: GENERALIZE "BREAK" TO OTHER BEHAVIORS**

Once it's solid on the place bed, apply the same pattern to other behaviors.

### **For Sit:**

|**Step**|**You Do**|**She Does**|
|---|---|---|
|1|Cue "sit"|Sits (butt on ground)|
|2|Wait 3 seconds|Holds the sit|
|3|Say "BREAK" + toss treat away|Gets up to get treat|

**Progress through phases:** Toss ‚Üí Delay ‚Üí No toss needed

---

### **For Meal Wait:**

|**Step**|**You Do**|**She Does**|
|---|---|---|
|1|Set bowl down, say "wait"|Stays back (any position)|
|2|Wait 3-5 seconds|Holds position|
|3|Say "BREAK"|Moves toward bowl|

**Note:** No toss needed here - the bowl is the reward.

---

### **For Crate Exit (With Wire Crate):**

|**Step**|**You Do**|**She Does**|
|---|---|---|
|1|Approach crate|She's sitting inside (butt down)|
|2|Open door fully|Holds position (visible through wire)|
|3|Say "BREAK"|Exits crate|
|4|Reward immediately outside|Gets treat/praise|

**Benefit of wire crate:** Clear visibility = you can see exactly when she's holding vs. breaking position.

---

## **THRESHOLD MANNERS PROTOCOL (WIRE CRATE)**

Once you have the wire crate, combine "break" training with threshold manners.

### **Full Protocol:**

|**Step**|**You Do**|**She Does**|**You Mark/Reward**|
|---|---|---|---|
|1|Approach crate door|Anything (sitting, standing, etc.)|-|
|2|Put hand on door latch|If she moves toward door, freeze and wait|-|
|3|Wait|She sits or settles back|"GOOD" (calm marker)|
|4|Open door 1 inch|If she moves, close door immediately|-|
|5|Wait|She stays in position|"GOOD"|
|6|Open door fully|She HOLDS position|"GOOD"|
|7|Say "BREAK"|NOW she can come out|Reward outside crate|

**Key Principles:**

- Door closing = consequence for breaking position
- Door opening = reward for holding position
- "BREAK" = permission to exit

---

## **WHY SHE STARES AT YOU INSTEAD OF BREAKING**

**What's Actually Happening:**

1. She hears "break"
2. She thinks "Is that a cue? What should I do?"
3. She defaults to holding the behavior (sit, place, etc.) because that's been reinforced
4. She stares at you for more information

**This Is Actually GOOD:**

- ‚úÖ She's engaged with you
- ‚úÖ She's looking for clarity
- ‚úÖ She's defaulting to impulse control (holding position)

**What She Needs:** For "break" to be taught as clearly as "sit" or "place" were taught.

---

## **WHY THE WIRE CRATE WILL HELP**

### **Problem 1: "Break" Isn't Clear**

**Wire crate solution:**

- Clear visibility for threshold manners practice
- You can SEE when she breaks vs. holds position
- Clear feedback loop = faster learning

### **Problem 2: Can't Tell If She's "In Position"**

**Wire crate solution:**

- Perfect visibility through wire
- You know EXACTLY when she's sitting, breaking, or holding
- You can time your "break" cue precisely

---

## **TRAINING TIMELINE**

### **Week 1: Place Bed Foundation**

- **Phase 1:** Place + toss (3 days)
- **Phase 2:** Place + delayed toss (3-5 days)
- **Goal:** She moves off bed when she hears "break"

### **Week 2: No Lure + Generalization**

- **Phase 3:** Place without toss
- **Add:** Meal wait "break"
- **Goal:** "Break" works without luring

### **Week 3: Full Generalization**

- **Add:** Sit "break"
- **Add:** Crate threshold "break" (with new wire crate)
- **Goal:** "Break" is reliable across all behaviors

### **Week 4: Consistency & Duration**

- **Practice:** All contexts
- **Add:** Longer durations before "break"
- **Goal:** Rock-solid release cue

---

## **TROUBLESHOOTING**

### **If She Doesn't Move When You Say "Break":**

- Go back to Phase 1 (toss the treat)
- Make sure your tone is enthusiastic
- Ensure she's actually "in position" before you release her

### **If She Breaks Before You Say "Break":**

- Don't reward the break
- Reset and try again
- Make the duration shorter (she's not ready for longer holds yet)

### **If She's Confused:**

- Simplify: go back to place bed only
- Increase reward value (better treats)
- Shorten duration (2 seconds instead of 5)

---

## **DAILY PRACTICE INTEGRATION**

### **Where to Practice "Break" Daily:**

|**Context**|**When**|**Reps**|
|---|---|---|
|**Place bed**|During bonus training sessions|10-20|
|**Meal wait**|Both meals (breakfast & dinner)|2|
|**Crate exit**|Every time she exits crate|3-5|
|**Sit practice**|During courtyard session|5-10|

**Total daily reps:** 20-37 (plenty to build the behavior)

---

## **SUCCESS METRICS**

### **You'll Know "Break" Is Working When:**

‚úÖ She moves immediately when she hears "break"  
‚úÖ She doesn't anticipate - she waits for the cue  
‚úÖ It works across different behaviors (place, sit, crate)  
‚úÖ It works in different locations  
‚úÖ You feel confident releasing her because you can SEE she's in position

---

## **FINAL NOTES**

**You're Not Doing Anything Wrong:** "Break" just needs to be taught systematically like any other behavior. The place bed toss method is the right start - you just need more reps and generalization.

**The Wire Crate Is a Game-Changer:** Clear visibility + solid door = perfect setup for teaching threshold manners and "break" properly.

**Be Patient:** This typically takes 2-4 weeks to fully solidify. That's normal. Progress, not perfection.

---

**START WITH:** Phase 1 on the place bed, 20 reps per session, 2-3 sessions per day.

**MEASURE:** Does she start moving off the bed when she hears "break"?

**PROGRESS:** Once she's reliably moving on the cue, move to Phase 2.

